      },
      "Untergruppe_RoteListen": {
        "content": "Arthropoden",
        "evidence_anchor": "These lists include a categorization of forest affinities for all species of Crassiclitellata: Lumbricidae (earth worms), Araneae (spiders), Opiliones (harvestmen), Pseudoscorpiones (pseudoscorpions), Hemiptera: Heteroptera (true bugs), Coleoptera (beetles), Hymenoptera: Aculeata (ants, bees, wasps), Lepidoptera: Macrolepidoptera (butterflies, moths partly) and Aves (birds) known from Germany."
      },
      "Lebensraum": {
        "content": "Wald",
        "evidence_anchor": "Since 2011 a list of the forest affinities of all forest species of vascular plants, bryophytes, and ferns known from Germany, is available. Recently, the first comparable lists of the forest affinities of animal species were published. These lists include a categorization of forest affinities for all species of Crassiclitellata: Lumbricidae (earth worms), Araneae (spiders), Opiliones (harvestmen), Pseudoscorpiones (pseudoscorpions), Hemiptera: Heteroptera (true bugs), Coleoptera (beetles), Hymenoptera: Aculeata (ants, bees, wasps), Lepidoptera: Macrolepidoptera (butterflies, moths partly) and Aves (birds) known from Germany."
      },
      "Antwortvariable": {
        "content": "Artenzahl",
        "evidence_anchor": "A summary of the forest affinities for all 11883 species represented in the forest affinity lists (Table 1) reveals that 38.0% of the species established in Germany (4517 species) are not associated with forest habitats (category “o”), whereas roughly one third of the fauna (4169 species, 35.1%) occurs in both forest and open habitats (categories “m”, “mm”, “mo”)."
      },
      "Trend": {
        "content": "negative",
        "evidence_anchor": "The results indicate that open landscape species are particularly threatened. With exception of Lumbricidae (only two threatened species in Germany), species of open landscapes are overrepresented in the group of threatened species in all species groups (Fig. 2). Across all 8 higher taxa, the largest fraction of threatened species is found among species only occurring in open landscapes (O; about 50%). The lowest fraction of threatened species with known forest affinity is found in species predominantly living in forests (F; about 21%). Species occurring in forests and open landscapes but not predominantly in forests (M) show an intermediate percentage of threatened species (about 25%)."
      }
    }
  ]
}

